I've just started sighting in an air rifle  and I think I've read
enough of the basics to get it done correctly.

However, one the things I'm wondering about are  the tradeoffs of
adjusting the height of the sight at the front or the back.  My
googling hasn't found an answer on this one so here goes:

Of course the standard way to do this is the adjustable rear sight.
However, in my air rifle case the front site is one of those ring
cylinder sights with the replaceable appertures.  So if I want to raise
my point of impact I could either raise the rear adjustable sight or I
could replace that front apperture with one that sticks up less.  It
would seem to me that I would be better off with a front sight that
sticks up the minimum ammount since I would think that it would reduce
parallax error.  There must be a flaw in that argument as I notice that
most of iron sights on target rifles  sit up quite high on the end of
the barrel.  What is the reason for that?  Easier to align your eyeball
vision line of sight, or something like that?  Parallax not really an
issue?

The other  reason for asking is that currently on this air rifle to get
the point of impact right I have to raise that rear sight up quite a
bit.  It sticks up so high that I can't help but feel like it will  get
hung on objects  or a rifle case and potentially mess up the setting
during handling.

If someone has a url that explains this aspect please point me in that
direction.

tks
Don

