A) you can adjust your sites in either way you describe above. Most
people just diddle with the adjustment instead of diddling with the
post.
B) paralax is an optical phenomonom that happens in scopes, but does
not happen in iron sites. Paralax happens when the reticule is not at
the exact focal point of the objective (First focal plane scope) or is
not at the exact focal point of the erector lens group (second focal
plane scopes.) This sets up a situation where the image may be in crisp
focus, but the reticule is not; and thereby, when you move your eye
around in the exit pupil of the scope the reticule moves around.
C) the height of the sites over the rifle barrel changes your view of
the trajectory of the projectile. But a couple of millimeters of change
(what you describe above) is irrelevent, while an inch of change (what
happens when you mount a scope) is relevent and noticible.

Mitch

