On my AR-15 the front post is about 3x as wide as the bullseye at the
200 and 300 yard line. I haven't had the opportunity to shoot further.
By putting the center of the top of the front post where the bull is
the widest, works best for me. Since I'm shooting service rifle, I do
not  have a lot of different front sight choices. I'm sticking with the
wider front post because it is easier to see in low light conditions.
The range where I have been shooting most is a 200 yard reduced range
near Saint Johnsbury, Vermont. There is hazy fog early in the morning
and the sun only rises above the mountain and hits the targets near
1100 in the morning.

I'm shooting about 95% at 200 yards. Not too many Xs though. New year's
resolution is to practice more.

